michael frank the nature and scope of statistical learning department of psychology stanford university department of psychology search psychology web site michael frank the nature and scope of statistical learning navigation people research and experiments education and training events related programs resources job opportunities about us user login sunet id login home michael frank the nature and scope of statistical learning speaker michael frank location jordan hall building 420 room 050 distributional learning learning about words from the company they keep in spoken language has recently been suggested as a candidate learning mechanism supporting several aspects of language acquisition including most prominently word segmentation experimental evidence suggests that adults and children can use some sort of distributional learning mechanism to identify words in spoken speech statistical learning but the nature of this process is still largely unknown and there is still debate about whether statistical learning is useful in language acquisition i will present work on statistical segmentation with adults that attempts to characterize the nature of statistical learning by comparing behavioral results to computational models of segmentation i ll also briefly describe some experiments on the scope of statistical learning and its applicability to slightly more natural artificial languages including testing some very large languages that are listened to over ten days and retained for months date and time friday 24 september 2010 3 15pm stanford home contact us maps and directions department of psychology jordan hall building 01 420 stanford university 450 serra mall stanford ca 94305 tel 650 725 2400 fax 650 725 5699
